.Malaik, this is where many developers get confused in interviews:

Load Balancer vs Reverse Proxy vs API Gateway vs Service Mesh

They sound similar because all of them sit in the network path, but each solves a different problem.

Let’s build it step by step.


---

1. Load Balancer

First problem in any system:

What if 10,000 users hit your server at the same time?

One server will crash.

So we run multiple servers.

Server 1
Server 2
Server 3
Server 4

But users should not know which server to call.

So we place a load balancer in front.

Client
   ↓
Load Balancer
   ↓
Server1
Server2
Server3
Server4

The load balancer distributes traffic.

Example algorithms:

• Round robin
• Least connections
• Weighted routing

Example tools:

• AWS ELB / ALB
• NGINX
• HAProxy


---

Interview answer

> A load balancer distributes incoming requests across multiple servers so that no single server gets overloaded. It improves scalability, availability, and fault tolerance.




---

2. Reverse Proxy

A reverse proxy sits in front of backend servers.

Client never talks to backend directly.

Client
   ↓
Reverse Proxy
   ↓
Backend Servers

Responsibilities:

• routing requests
• hiding internal services
• SSL termination
• caching
• compression

Example:

/api/users → user service
/api/orders → order service

Tools:

• NGINX
• Apache
• Traefik


---

Interview answer

> A reverse proxy sits between clients and backend servers. It receives requests from clients and forwards them to the appropriate backend service while providing features like routing, SSL termination, caching, and security.




---

3. API Gateway

When microservices appear, complexity explodes.

Example services:

User Service
Order Service
Payment Service
Metadata Service
Notification Service

Without gateway:

Frontend → 5 services

This is messy.

So we add API Gateway.

Client
   ↓
API Gateway
   ↓
Microservices

API Gateway responsibilities:

• request routing
• authentication (JWT, OAuth)
• rate limiting
• API versioning
• logging
• request aggregation

Tools:

• Spring Cloud Gateway
• AWS API Gateway
• Kong
• Zuul


---

Interview answer

> API Gateway is the single entry point for client requests in a microservice architecture. It handles routing, authentication, rate limiting, monitoring, and forwards requests to the appropriate microservice.




---

4. Service Mesh (very important concept)

This is where things get interesting.

API Gateway handles client → service communication.

But microservices also talk to each other.

Example:

Order Service → Payment Service
Order Service → Inventory Service
Inventory Service → Notification Service

When services talk to each other, problems appear:

• retries
• timeouts
• circuit breaking
• service discovery
• encryption
• traffic control

Developers shouldn't write all this logic.

So we use Service Mesh.

In service mesh, every service gets a sidecar proxy.

Example:

Service A + Envoy Proxy
Service B + Envoy Proxy
Service C + Envoy Proxy

Communication becomes:

Service A
   ↓
Sidecar Proxy
   ↓
Sidecar Proxy
   ↓
Service B

Service mesh handles:

• retries
• load balancing
• service discovery
• mTLS security
• observability
• traffic routing

Popular tools:

• Istio
• Linkerd
• Consul


---

Interview answer

> Service mesh manages service-to-service communication inside a microservices architecture. It provides features like retries, circuit breaking, load balancing, observability, and security without adding that logic inside application code.




---

5. The full real-world architecture

In big systems it looks like this:

Client
   ↓
CDN
   ↓
Load Balancer
   ↓
API Gateway
   ↓
Microservices
   ↓
Service Mesh
   ↓
Databases

Each layer solves a different problem.


